ce:section.ce:para:
According the present results and the previous literature reports [69-73], we propose that under interaction of light (mainly UV light), DT anion is excited to generate the photo-electron (e-) and electron-deficient oxygen species (hole, h+, usually marked as wO species in the literature [69-73]) that are capable of carrying out reduction and oxidation reactions, respectively. Then the wO species, as a super oxidant, easily deprives one H atom from the oxidizable CH bond of RH to yield its one-electron reduced state and a C-centered free radical (·R) through a PET pathway. Finally, under the participation of O2, the reduced DT anion is re-oxidized to its starting oxidative state to achieve catalyst cycling and the produced R· radical can turn into the oxygenated products (ROH and R = O, Scheme 1
                        ) [71-73]. We previously reported that CQD can be encapsulated by TBA micelle to form its cationized hybridizer under hydrothermal condition and the latter is easily combined with DT anion via electrostatic interaction to produce the CQD- TBADT [43]. It is expected that 3d transient metal ion-modified CQD should more easily form a hybrid with TBADT than pure CQD, which should be owing to the enhanced cationization and coordination effects, thereby helping to improve the synthetic quality, structural stability, redox capacity and visible light harvesting efficiency of TBADT, and to especially accelerate a transfer of its photo-generated electrons toward the dopant Mn+/CQD. In addition, the doped Ni2+/CQD may contribute to the reductive activation of O2 by the photo-electron (e-) to the •O2 
                        – species and the latter more easily combines with the R• radical to form the peroxy anion (ROO-) compared to the relatively inert O2. These favorable hybridization effects play a critical role in hoisting the photo-catalysis performance of TBADT [33]. The modified metal ions can fine-tune the above hybridization effects via the coordination ability regulated by their 3d electrons. According to a classical coordination field theory, Ni2+(d8) has a stronger coordination ability than Co2+(d7) and especially Cu2+(d10) [74] and thereby presents the best fine-tuning effect, as supported by the above reaction and characterization results.
